Western Cape South African Police Service (SAPS) are on a recruitment drive to get more police officers. They are looking for matriculated South African citizens between the ages of 18 and under 30 years old. Applicants must be in possession of a light motor vehicle driving license. However,  10% of the total allocation of trainees will be allowed without a driving license. Applicants must also submit themselves to a physical fitness examination as well as a psychometric test and have a body mass index of less than 30. SAPS Spokesperson in the Western Cape, Captain Hein Hendricks says that SAPS is in the process of recruiting over 1100 police officers for the Western Cape. “We are looking for a big response because the closing date is on January 18,  so we encouraging all recruits, preferably residing in the Western Cape, but we are also looking at the boarders of the Western Cape and applicants are encouraged to go to the nearest police station or to contact the recruitment centre in Cape Town.” The entire program will run for 21 months according to Captain Hendricks. Click on audio below: <a href="https://iono.fm/e/644033">Content hosted by iono.fm</a>